00:00:30.460 --> 00:00:32.180
and circadian rhythms.

00:00:32.180 --> 00:00:34.440
Today we talk about thermoregulation,

00:00:34.440 --> 00:00:36.890
how the body heats and cools itself,

00:00:36.890 --> 00:00:39.700
and maintains what we call homeostasis,

00:00:39.700 --> 00:00:41.810
which is an equilibrium of processes

00:00:41.810 --> 00:00:45.350
that keeps our neurons healthy,
our organs functioning well.

00:00:45.350 --> 00:00:48.313
And as Dr. Heller teaches us,

00:00:48.313 --> 00:00:50.190
thermoregulation could
be leveraged in order

00:00:50.190 --> 00:00:52.490
to greatly increase our performance

00:00:52.490 --> 00:00:55.750
in athletics and mental
performance as well.

00:00:55.750 --> 00:00:58.230
Learning to control your
core body temperature

00:00:58.230 --> 00:00:59.500
is one of the most,

00:00:59.500 --> 00:01:02.300
if not the most powerful
thing that you can do

00:01:02.300 --> 00:01:04.600
to optimize mental and
physical performance,

00:01:04.600 --> 00:01:06.860
regardless of the
environment that you're in.

00:01:06.860 --> 00:01:09.470
He also dispels many
common myths about heating

00:01:09.470 --> 00:01:10.940
and cooling the body,

00:01:10.940 --> 00:01:13.770
including the idea that putting
a cold pack on your head

00:01:13.770 --> 00:01:16.330
or neck is the optimal
way to cool down quickly.

00:01:16.330 --> 00:01:17.570
And in fact,

00:01:17.570 --> 00:01:20.510
as Dr Heller tells us, it
actually can be counterproductive,

00:01:20.510 --> 00:01:22.790
and lead to hyperthermia.

00:01:22.790 --> 00:01:25.210
