of endurance work or aerobic
work, running, cycling,

00:47:50.050 --> 00:47:51.720
things of that sort.

00:47:51.720 --> 00:47:54.460
- Well, one of the problems with,

00:47:54.460 --> 00:47:59.460
for us, is that our equipment
now is not really portable.

00:47:59.770 --> 00:48:01.540
I mean, it's portable in
the sense that you can carry

00:48:01.540 --> 00:48:04.010
it to the gym or to the football field.

00:48:04.010 --> 00:48:05.039
- But you're not going
to run or run with it.

00:48:05.039 --> 00:48:07.024
- But you're not going
to run with it, right.

00:48:07.024 --> 00:48:07.857
- Or equip a bicycle with it.

00:48:07.857 --> 00:48:11.320
Although when are the cooling
handles on bicycles coming?

00:48:11.320 --> 00:48:12.153
- That would be good,

00:48:12.153 --> 00:48:15.810
but one itinerant activity is golfing.

00:48:15.810 --> 00:48:19.079
And people have put it
on their golf carts, and-

00:48:19.079 --> 00:48:20.950
- Do people really heat
up that much in golf?

00:48:20.950 --> 00:48:21.783
- They do.

00:48:21.783 --> 00:48:23.140
- Not to be disparaging of the golfers,

00:48:23.140 --> 00:48:25.300
but the way I conceptualize golf,

00:48:25.300 --> 00:48:27.610
it's like a swing and then a walk

00:48:27.610 --> 00:48:29.530
and then a cart ride and then a meal.

00:48:29.530 --> 00:48:31.770
I probably just offended
all the golfers out there.

00:48:31.770 --> 00:48:35.400
- Well, one time we were doing work

00:48:36.350 --> 00:48:39.030
for the Department of Defense.

00:48:39.030 --> 00:48:40.620
And they wanted to check it out,

00:48:40.620 --> 00:48:43.770
whether or not what we were
doing was really worthwhile.

00:48:43.770 --> 00:48:45.720
So they sent out a team of

00:48:47.363 --> 00:48:51.560
special ops soldiers to be
our subjects and test it out.

00:48:51.560 --> 00:48:56.090
They were here for a week.
So they that was a fun week.

00:48:56.090 --> 00:48:57.920
- Yeah, I do some work with those guys.

00:48:57.920 --> 00:49:00.140
They're hard driving guys.

00:49:00.140 --> 00:49:01.690
They also know how to have fun.

00:49:02.547 --> 00:49:04.950
But yeah, they definitely have,

00:49:04.950 --> 00:49:07.750
if they have an off or a quit switch,

00:49:07.750 --> 00:49:11.440
it's buried deep within
their nervous system.

00:49:11.440 --> 00:49:13.690
They don't like to hit that quit switch.

00:49:13.690 --> 00:49:16.340
- So the guy who wrote the final report,

00:49:16.340 --> 00:49:19.710
he gave an addendum to the
report and he said, "Well,

00:49:19.710 --> 00:49:20.810
I'll tell you this.

00:49:20.810 --> 00:49:22.720
After I've gotten home,

00:49:22.720 --> 00:49:24.300
it's added that technology,"

00:49:24.300 --> 00:49:25.820
they took the technology with them.

00:49:25.820 --> 00:49:27.170
They wanted to keep it.
- Oh, Yeah.

00:49:27.170 --> 00:49:28.370
That sounds about right.

00:49:29.300 --> 00:49:31.660
- And using it, it has added 20 yards

00:49:31.660 --> 00:49:33.220
to every club in my bag.

00:49:33.220 --> 00:49:35.300
And that's no effin' small deal.

00:49:35.300 --> 00:49:38.180
- Wow, so it's allowing
people to hit further,

00:49:38.180 --> 00:49:40.340
hit their golf ball further?
- Right. [chuckles]

00:49:40.340 --> 00:49:43.150
- Interesting. All right.

00:49:43.150 --> 00:49:46.703
So for the golf players out there,

00:49:50.900 --> 00:49:52.480
that's the reward you get back from Craig

00:49:52.480 --> 00:49:54.233
for all my little knocks on golf.

00:49:55.246 --> 00:49:56.130
I don't have any knock on golf.

00:49:56.130 --> 00:49:59.720
I just don't think about it
as a sport where heating up

00:49:59.720 --> 00:50:01.020
is a limiting factor.

00:50:01.020 --> 00:50:05.000
So since they're getting
more out of their drive,

00:50:05.000 --> 00:50:06.350
what do you think's going on there?

00:50:06.350 --> 00:50:08.643
- Well, they can be heating up.

00:50:08.643 --> 00:50:09.804
- And they wear gloves, right?

00:50:09.804 --> 00:50:11.930
- They're wearing glove on
a hot day, and so forth.

00:50:11.930 --> 00:50:14.700
But let me just tell you
one more serious story

00:50:14.700 --> 00:50:17.400
about golfers and that is individuals

00:50:17.400 --> 00:50:19.450
with multiple sclerosis

00:50:19.450 --> 00:50:21.760
are exceedingly temperature-sensitive.

00:50:21.760 --> 00:50:24.820
- I didn't know that.
- So they may still be mobile,

00:50:24.820 --> 00:50:27.060
but they have to stay in cool locations

00:50:27.060 --> 00:50:31.260
and not increase their
exercise to any great extent.

00:50:31.260 --> 00:50:35.450
But we've had subjects
with multiple sclerosis

00:50:35.450 --> 00:50:37.590
who have just essentially put the device

00:50:37.590 --> 00:50:39.580
on their golf cart and
they're back out playing golf

00:50:39.580 --> 00:50:40.570
in the middle of the summer.

00:50:40.570 --> 00:50:41.690
- Oh, that's great.
- Yeah.

00:50:41.690 --> 00:50:43.010
- That's great.

00:50:43.010 --> 00:50:46.230
Anything that allows people
to have normal levels of

00:50:47.460 --> 00:50:50.680
livelihood and recreation is great.

00:50:50.680 --> 00:50:52.520
We always think about performance

00:50:52.520 --> 00:50:54.510
at these kinds of like
peak and elite levels

00:50:54.510 --> 00:50:56.690
and pushing harder, but yeah,

00:50:56.690 --> 00:50:57.700
anything that allows people

00:50:57.700 --> 00:51:00.490
to be mobile and functional is great.

00:51:00.490 --> 00:51:04.900
So what's your favorite
example of endurance,

00:51:04.900 --> 00:51:06.820
and feel free to give us the extreme one

00:51:06.820 --> 00:51:08.520
and then we'll talk about averages

00:51:09.730 --> 00:51:10.580
to make sure we're thorough

00:51:10.580 --> 00:51:12.900
about averages versus exceptions.

00:51:12.900 --> 00:51:16.760
- Right. We haven't
done a lot in the field.

00:51:16.760 --> 00:51:18.700
I mean outdoors.

00:51:18.700 --> 00:51:22.320
Most of our endurance
has been in a hot room

00:51:22.320 --> 00:51:24.100
with treadmill work, and so forth.

00:51:24.100 --> 00:51:26.410
So the very first experiment we had,

00:51:26.410 --> 00:51:29.340
I think, maybe 18 subjects
just off the street.

00:51:29.340 --> 00:51:32.140
Maybe we just recruited
people in the hallways,

00:51:32.140 --> 00:51:33.520
come on in and do this.

00:51:33.520 --> 00:51:36.930
And what we found is we could,

00:51:36.930 --> 00:51:39.930
for this group with one trial
with and without cooling,

00:51:39.930 --> 00:51:43.650
we could double their endurance,
walking on the treadmill,

00:51:43.650 --> 00:51:46.010
walking uphill on the
treadmill in the heat,

00:51:46.010 --> 00:51:48.400
like maybe 40 degrees ambient temperature,

00:51:48.400 --> 00:51:49.600
40 degrees centigrade.

00:51:49.600 --> 00:51:50.970
- So what does the experiment look like?

00:51:50.970 --> 00:51:54.120
You're having people walk on
an incline. It's really warm.

00:51:54.120 --> 00:51:56.700
Some people are just going to
hit the quit button and say,

00:51:56.700 --> 00:51:59.010
I've had enough and get off the treadmill

00:51:59.010 --> 00:52:00.560
with proper cooling.

00:52:00.560 --> 00:52:02.560
When are they doing the cooling?

00:52:02.560 --> 00:52:04.270
- They're doing it continuously.

00:52:04.270 --> 00:52:06.570
- I see.
- Because in the laboratory,

00:52:06.570 --> 00:52:10.500
we can suspend devices from
the ceiling, for example.

00:52:10.500 --> 00:52:13.290
Now we do have prototype wearable devices.

00:52:13.290 --> 00:52:18.290
We did them in response to
emails from Ebola workers

00:52:18.810 --> 00:52:22.010
a number of years ago in Sierra Leone.

00:52:22.010 --> 00:52:24.170
They said, "We've read about
your work with athletes.

00:52:24.170 --> 00:52:25.510
Can't you do something for us?

00:52:25.510 --> 00:52:27.650
I mean, we're in the
personal protective gear,

00:52:27.650 --> 00:52:29.860
and we can't be in the
hot zone for more than 15

00:52:29.860 --> 00:52:31.550
or 20 minutes."

00:52:31.550 --> 00:52:34.800
So that was started us on the challenge

00:52:34.800 --> 00:52:37.913
of developing wearable systems
that could go under the PPE.

00:52:39.220 --> 00:52:40.820
We've published that work now, but-.

00:52:40.820 --> 00:52:42.140
- That's great, and I'm guessing

00:52:42.140 --> 00:52:44.610
the military special operators
that are out in the desert

00:52:44.610 --> 00:52:46.690
and other locations are probably excited

00:52:46.690 --> 00:52:47.990
about this technology.

00:52:47.990 --> 00:52:50.205
- Well, once they get it.
- Once they get.

00:52:50.205 --> 00:52:52.050
It's coming, it's coming.

00:52:52.050 --> 00:52:55.640
Yeah, I think some people might wonder,

00:52:55.640 --> 00:52:56.790
if there are all these studies

00:52:56.790 --> 00:52:59.230
and there are these incredible
results over the years

00:52:59.230 --> 00:53:00.640
on why haven't we heard more about it?

00:53:00.640 --> 00:53:02.960
And I will ask your
opinion on that as well.

00:53:02.960 --> 00:53:04.970
But I'll just editorialize a little bit.

00:53:04.970 --> 00:53:09.500
Is that the best laboratory work

00:53:09.500 --> 00:53:11.090
in its practical applications

00:53:11.090 --> 00:53:13.913
oftentimes requires many studies.

00:53:14.910 --> 00:53:19.440
And oftentimes there isn't
a portal, so to speak,

00:53:19.440 --> 00:53:22.180
to get that information out
into the technology sector.

00:53:22.180 --> 00:53:25.780
So there is a company that's
developing this technology

00:53:25.780 --> 00:53:30.480
for people to use, to purchase and use.

00:53:30.480 --> 00:53:31.470
You might as well just tell us now,

00:53:31.470 --> 00:53:33.410
what is the name of that company?

00:53:33.410 --> 00:53:34.870
And do they have a website?

00:53:34.870 --> 00:53:36.250
People are going to want to know

00:53:36.250 --> 00:53:39.210
where can they get this
magical technology?

00:53:39.210 --> 00:53:42.040
And is there a poor man's
version of it as well?

00:53:42.040 --> 00:53:46.270
- Well, the company is
Arteria, A-R-T-E-R-I-A,

00:53:46.270 --> 00:53:49.947
and the website is www.coolmitt.com.

00:53:51.980 --> 00:53:56.980
So CoolMitt is just
C-O-O-L-M-I-T-T. coolmitt.com

00:53:57.230 --> 00:53:58.260
- It's a great website.

00:53:58.260 --> 00:54:00.150
When I went there, it says that right now,

00:54:00.150 --> 00:54:01.700
the technology is only available

00:54:01.700 --> 00:54:04.060
to professional sports teams and military.

00:54:04.060 --> 00:54:04.893
Is that true?

00:54:04.893 --> 00:54:05.990
- Well, where we stand now

00:54:05.990 --> 00:54:08.720
is the new version of the technology

00:54:08.720 --> 00:54:10.660
is sort of in beta test versions.

00:54:10.660 --> 00:54:12.560
We got it into the hands of people

00:54:12.560 --> 00:54:14.550
who had used the technology before.

00:54:14.550 --> 00:54:18.300
So there's NFL teams that are using.

00:54:18.300 --> 00:54:22.060
There's college teams. There's Olympics.

00:54:22.060 --> 00:54:24.093
There's the Navy SEALs,

00:54:25.110 --> 00:54:27.690
Major League Baseball, the NBA,

00:54:27.690 --> 00:54:29.480
the National Tennis Association.

00:54:29.480 --> 00:54:33.940
They have locations where
now they are trying this out

00:54:33.940 --> 00:54:35.600
and reporting back, how's it working?

00:54:35.600 --> 00:54:36.560
How could you change it?

00:54:36.560 --> 00:54:38.900
How could you improve it? And so forth.

00:54:38.900 --> 00:54:40.660
So that's where we are.

00:54:40.660 --> 00:54:42.940
But on the website,

00:54:42.940 --> 00:54:47.000
you can actually sign up for
being one who will be able

00:54:47.000 --> 00:54:48.720
to get one [chuckles]

00:54:48.720 --> 00:54:50.550
when they are finally manufactured.

00:54:50.550 --> 00:54:52.970
They're now being made
in fairly small lots,

00:54:52.970 --> 00:54:56.160
because you want to change
things as you realize how

00:54:56.160 --> 00:54:57.090
it can be improved.

00:54:57.090 --> 00:54:58.460
- Yeah. This is Stanford after all.

00:54:58.460 --> 00:55:00.470
You want to get the technology right.

00:55:00.470 --> 00:55:03.290
I like to joke that one of
the reasons I like being

00:55:03.290 --> 00:55:04.580
at Stanford so much is that,

00:55:04.580 --> 00:55:06.310
not only are my colleagues amazing

00:55:06.310 --> 00:55:07.680
and they're so forward thinking,

00:55:07.680 --> 00:55:09.330
but they're all perfectionists.

00:55:09.330 --> 00:55:11.320
And so that the perfectionist mindset

00:55:11.320 --> 00:55:15.960
is it has to be perfect before
it can go live, so to speak.

00:55:15.960 --> 00:55:18.440
Well, I think there will
be a lot of interest.

00:55:18.440 --> 00:55:20.910
Let's talk about the technology in

00:55:20.910 --> 00:55:22.230
a little more detail for a moment.

00:55:22.230 --> 00:55:25.270
And then let's talk about
whether or not cruder forms

00:55:25.270 --> 00:55:27.870
of that technology exist
either for sake of safety

00:55:27.870 --> 00:55:29.173
and/or performance.

00:55:30.190 --> 00:55:34.460
So what is, the CoolMitt,
as I understand is

00:55:34.460 --> 00:55:35.670
it's a mitt, it's a glove.

00:55:35.670 --> 00:55:36.610
You put your hand into,

00:55:36.610 --> 00:55:39.400
you hold on to a surface.

00:55:39.400 --> 00:55:42.330
And that surface cools your hand

00:55:42.330 --> 00:55:46.160
and thereby through
this specialized portal,

00:55:46.160 --> 00:55:47.627
cools your core body temperature

00:55:47.627 --> 00:55:50.090
and all the muscles of the body.

00:55:50.090 --> 00:55:53.240
Subjectively, if I were
to do this right now,

00:55:53.240 --> 00:55:55.300
would I think that it was ice cold

00:55:55.300 --> 00:55:58.300
or would I think it was just cool?

00:55:58.300 --> 00:55:59.550
- Just cool.
- I see.

00:55:59.550 --> 00:56:01.630
- Ice cold is too cold.

00:56:01.630 --> 00:56:03.100
So people always ask, well,

00:56:03.100 --> 00:56:05.840
why can't you just stick your
hand in a bucket of ice water?

00:56:05.840 --> 00:56:07.150
It's too cold.

00:56:07.150 --> 00:56:09.520
What that does is that causes reflex,

00:56:09.520 --> 00:56:13.880
a vasoconstriction of the very
portals that you're trying

00:56:13.880 --> 00:56:16.620
to maximize the heat loss from.

00:56:16.620 --> 00:56:18.867
So you stick your hand in cold water,

00:56:18.867 --> 00:56:20.330
and when it comes out, it's cold.

00:56:20.330 --> 00:56:22.100
- You just sealed up all the heat

00:56:22.100 --> 00:56:22.933
in your body.
- Yeah.

00:56:22.933 --> 00:56:26.410
Right, so what I sort of recommended

00:56:26.410 --> 00:56:27.850
to someone at one point,

00:56:27.850 --> 00:56:29.340
they said, "Well, when I'm running,

00:56:29.340 --> 00:56:31.970
can't I just carry a frozen juice can,

00:56:31.970 --> 00:56:33.410
and it will gradually melt?"

00:56:33.410 --> 00:56:34.310
And I said, "Well, no,

00:56:34.310 --> 00:56:37.240
because that's going to
decrease the heat loss

00:56:37.240 --> 00:56:38.073
from that hand.

00:56:38.073 --> 00:56:40.544
But if every couple
minutes you switched hands,

00:56:40.544 --> 00:56:41.720
[chuckles] it might work.

00:56:41.720 --> 00:56:43.310
- Well, I have a feeling that there

00:56:43.310 --> 00:56:46.790
are people now doing that
as well as trying this.

00:56:46.790 --> 00:56:51.590
So how long, in the CoolMitt
at the proper temperature,

00:56:51.590 --> 00:56:55.460
how long are people putting
their hands into the Mitt?

00:56:55.460 --> 00:56:59.330
- We, once again, had just
standardized them three minutes.

00:56:59.330 --> 00:57:01.280
And part of the reason for that is that

00:57:02.830 --> 00:57:04.230
the rate of heat loss is

00:57:04.230 --> 00:57:07.640
an exponentially declining curve, okay?

00:57:07.640 --> 00:57:11.640
And three minutes sort of gets
the best part of the curve.

00:57:11.640 --> 00:57:14.280
So you can go longer and get more benefit,

00:57:14.280 --> 00:57:15.870
but the biggest bang for the buck

00:57:15.870 --> 00:57:18.550
is in the first two, three minutes.

00:57:18.550 --> 00:57:22.190
- Okay, you mentioned a number
of impressive organizations,

00:57:22.190 --> 00:57:24.560
sports teams, and military
that are using this.

00:57:24.560 --> 00:57:26.360
This is not something that I typically see

00:57:26.360 --> 00:57:28.120
on the sidelines of games.

00:57:28.120 --> 00:57:31.220
Although to be honest, I
haven't looked very carefully.

00:57:31.220 --> 00:57:34.320
I'm guessing that they
are probably keeping

00:57:34.320 --> 00:57:37.090
the technology somewhat under wraps.

00:57:37.090 --> 00:57:38.650
Where, and how are they doing this?

00:57:38.650 --> 00:57:40.210
Are they running back to the locker room?

00:57:40.210 --> 00:57:41.790
I mean, the military special operators

00:57:41.790 --> 00:57:42.623
are doing their thing,

00:57:42.623 --> 00:57:44.400
but in terms of the athletes,

00:57:44.400 --> 00:57:46.460
is it possible, hypothetically,

00:57:46.460 --> 00:57:51.070
that athletes are doing
this somewhat incognito?

00:57:51.070 --> 00:57:53.910
- It's possible, but I really don't know.

00:57:53.910 --> 00:57:56.420
People have mentioned here at Stanford,

00:57:56.420 --> 00:57:59.060
they don't see the football team using it.

00:57:59.060 --> 00:58:01.030
Well, the football team here at Stanford

00:58:01.030 --> 00:58:04.770
is mostly playing in cold
weather, cool weather.

00:58:04.770 --> 00:58:06.410
The night games are cool.

00:58:06.410 --> 00:58:09.440
Even day games are not
very hot frequently here.

00:58:09.440 --> 00:58:12.993
But when they go to a hot
place like Arizona or Utah,

00:58:13.875 --> 00:58:15.650
at least our coach,

00:58:15.650 --> 00:58:17.910
Shaw, says that they take it with them

00:58:17.910 --> 00:58:20.190
and that's when they find the benefit.

00:58:20.190 --> 00:58:21.260
That's when they use it.

00:58:21.260 --> 00:58:26.260
- Interesting, so is
there a poor person's,

00:58:27.570 --> 00:58:29.800
poor man or woman's version of this?

00:58:29.800 --> 00:58:31.710
You mentioned the juice
can passing back and forth.

00:58:31.710 --> 00:58:33.310
You mentioned cooling the hands.

00:58:34.709 --> 00:58:37.340
A number of people said
to me after learning

00:58:37.340 --> 00:58:39.810
a little bit about this
science and technology

00:58:39.810 --> 00:58:43.300
that they've experienced some big effects,

00:58:43.300 --> 00:58:46.410
positive effects of cooling by,

00:58:46.410 --> 00:58:47.450
and I confess, I've done this,

00:58:47.450 --> 00:58:50.430
taking a package of frozen blueberries,

00:58:50.430 --> 00:58:51.400
and just kind of passing it back

00:58:51.400 --> 00:58:52.250
and forth between my hands.

00:58:52.250 --> 00:58:53.167
Now talking to you,

00:58:53.167 --> 00:58:55.730
I realize I probably
didn't do it long enough.

00:58:55.730 --> 00:58:56.563
I probably was,

00:58:56.563 --> 00:58:59.580
I was only doing maybe 30
seconds passing it back

00:58:59.580 --> 00:59:02.450
and forth between my hands
and then going back into sets.

00:59:02.450 --> 00:59:06.380
I did see a performance
enhancing effect. Absolutely.

00:59:06.380 --> 00:59:10.950
But I realized I probably
wasn't optimizing the protocol.

00:59:10.950 --> 00:59:14.610
If you were going to give
a crude protocol for it,

00:59:14.610 --> 00:59:15.750
let's just say for the gym,

00:59:15.750 --> 00:59:17.560
because with running,
it's a little bit tricky,

00:59:17.560 --> 00:59:19.700
but what would that look like

00:59:19.700 --> 00:59:21.570
if people wanted to just play with this

00:59:21.570 --> 00:59:23.960
in some sort of fashion?

00:59:23.960 --> 00:59:28.810
- Well, it would be experimental.

00:59:28.810 --> 00:59:31.380
- Sure. Yeah, none of
that is very controlled.

00:59:31.380 --> 00:59:34.180
- Your idea of frozen peas is a good idea.

00:59:34.180 --> 00:59:38.160
And I think since there's
been no actual study of that,

00:59:38.160 --> 00:59:40.870
it would have to be you working out

00:59:40.870 --> 00:59:42.910
what is the best for you.

00:59:42.910 --> 00:59:46.130
But one way to figure it out is that if,

00:59:46.130 --> 00:59:50.420
after you hold the cold peas in one hand

00:59:50.420 --> 00:59:52.390
and you switch it to the other hand,

00:59:52.390 --> 00:59:55.180
if someone then comes in, feels your hand,

00:59:55.180 --> 00:59:56.920
is it warm or cold?

00:59:56.920 --> 00:59:59.970
If it's cold, it means
you vasoconstricted.

00:59:59.970 --> 01:00:04.440
If it's warm, it means the hot
blood is still going there.

01:00:04.440 --> 01:00:06.380
Okay. So we do that in the lab.

01:00:06.380 --> 01:00:08.740
- And the key is for it
to not vasoconstrict?

01:00:08.740 --> 01:00:09.870
- Right.
- Okay.

01:00:09.870 --> 01:00:11.240
So there's a test out there, folks.

01:00:11.240 --> 01:00:13.460
If you're going to try this
in kind of a crude fashion,

01:00:13.460 --> 01:00:14.293
at least until

01:00:15.516 --> 01:00:17.416
the CoolMitt is available more broadly

01:00:18.490 --> 01:00:19.883
to the general public,

01:00:21.510 --> 01:00:23.400
you want to assess whether or not

01:00:23.400 --> 01:00:28.066
your palms actually feel cool
to the touch by somebody else.

01:00:28.066 --> 01:00:28.899
And if it does,

01:00:28.899 --> 01:00:30.460
that means you've essentially
shut down the portal.

01:00:30.460 --> 01:00:32.680
You're sealing in more heat, which is bad.

01:00:32.680 --> 01:00:36.860
What about putting this
cold pack of some sort

01:00:36.860 --> 01:00:39.330
on the face or-

01:00:39.330 --> 01:00:40.440
- Or the feet?
- Or the feet?

01:00:40.440 --> 01:00:41.273
I work out at home.

01:00:41.273 --> 01:00:43.160
I don't often work out barefooted,

01:00:43.160 --> 01:00:45.770
but I suppose I could,
like they did in the 70s.

01:00:45.770 --> 01:00:48.380
When those guys were
walking around without shoes

01:00:48.380 --> 01:00:51.400
and squatting without
any shoes or socks on.

01:00:51.400 --> 01:00:53.770
Could I put my feet on them?

01:00:53.770 --> 01:00:54.653
- You could.

01:00:56.520 --> 01:00:59.060
If you simply had a water-profused pad

01:00:59.060 --> 01:01:01.750
and you were circulating
cool water through it,

01:01:01.750 --> 01:01:04.243
you could just put your feet on it, okay?

01:01:07.800 --> 01:01:12.380
Part of the problem is
that you don't want,

01:01:12.380 --> 01:01:16.690
if, let's say you have just
a cold pack of something.

01:01:16.690 --> 01:01:19.730
The problem is back to
boundary layers again.

01:01:19.730 --> 01:01:24.200
If you don't have a convective
stream of the cooling medium,

01:01:24.200 --> 01:01:26.000
the heat sink is not as effective,

01:01:26.000 --> 01:01:28.660
because there'll be a
boundary layer developed

01:01:28.660 --> 01:01:32.760
between the heat sink
material and your skin.

01:01:32.760 --> 01:01:35.360
So that decreases its efficacy.

01:01:35.360 --> 01:01:37.490
- I see, maybe we should
just for a moment,

01:01:37.490 --> 01:01:39.210
talk about convection,

01:01:39.210 --> 01:01:41.410
radiation, and convection,
and just make that clear.

01:01:41.410 --> 01:01:43.610
Like if I put my hands,

01:01:43.610 --> 01:01:45.850
let's say it's a cold
night and I'm at a campfire

01:01:45.850 --> 01:01:48.050
and I take my hands and I
put them out to the fire-

01:01:48.050 --> 01:01:50.520
- You're getting radiation.
- You're getting radiation.

01:01:50.520 --> 01:01:51.353
- Right.
- Okay.

01:01:51.353 --> 01:01:52.630
- Right.

01:01:52.630 --> 01:01:55.210
- And then if it's a windy warm night, no,

01:01:55.210 --> 01:01:56.610
I don't know if that's the best example.

01:01:56.610 --> 01:01:58.970
Give us a good example of convection.

01:01:58.970 --> 01:02:01.800
- Convection, sure, is in a cool breeze.

01:02:01.800 --> 01:02:05.340
The wind chill factor. That's
due to convection, okay?

01:02:05.340 --> 01:02:10.210
But in terms of heat
transfer between two objects,

01:02:10.210 --> 01:02:13.210
if you have convection of the medium,

01:02:13.210 --> 01:02:17.820
whether it's blood on the
inside and water on the outside,

01:02:17.820 --> 01:02:20.810
you increase the heat exchange

01:02:20.810 --> 01:02:23.100
if you have conviction on both sides.

01:02:23.100 --> 01:02:25.580
- Right, so this is why
just planting my feet

01:02:25.580 --> 01:02:27.530
on two packages of froze,

01:02:27.530 --> 01:02:29.830
my bare feet on two
packages of frozen peas,

01:02:29.830 --> 01:02:33.760
there's really no opportunity
for circulation of,

01:02:33.760 --> 01:02:34.900
and therefore heat transfer.

01:02:34.900 --> 01:02:37.570
So it's not really optimal, which, and I-

01:02:37.570 --> 01:02:38.880
- But once again,

01:02:38.880 --> 01:02:42.080
it depends on the surface area
to get any benefit at all.

01:02:42.080 --> 01:02:45.270
We have a study that we published,

01:02:45.270 --> 01:02:49.230
which was investigating
the standard treatment

01:02:49.230 --> 01:02:51.440
for hyperthermia in the field.

01:02:51.440 --> 01:02:54.093
And the standard treatment,

01:02:55.250 --> 01:02:58.330
as recommended by medical organizations,

01:02:58.330 --> 01:03:00.930
is you take cold packs and you put them

01:03:00.930 --> 01:03:03.180
in the axilla, the groin.

01:03:03.180 --> 01:03:05.210
- The axilla or the armpit.

01:03:05.210 --> 01:03:08.133
- The armpits, the groin, which is-

01:03:09.960 --> 01:03:11.650
- Thin-skinned, lots of vasculature.

01:03:11.650 --> 01:03:14.480
- Right, and the neck.

01:03:14.480 --> 01:03:16.760
So what we did is we did studies

01:03:16.760 --> 01:03:18.740
in which we made people hyperthermic.

01:03:18.740 --> 01:03:21.860
And then we measured the rate
at which we cool call them

01:03:22.710 --> 01:03:27.560
by putting those positions
in those heat exchange bags,

01:03:27.560 --> 01:03:30.790
in the recommended location
versus on the glabrous skin

01:03:30.790 --> 01:03:33.980
versus palms, soles, and face.

01:03:33.980 --> 01:03:36.530
The cooling rate was double.

01:03:36.530 --> 01:03:37.627
- Wow.

01:03:37.627 --> 01:03:39.980
- And we put the same ice packs,

01:03:39.980 --> 01:03:44.370
the same cold packs on the heat portals,

01:03:44.370 --> 01:03:47.920
rather than the axilla,
the groin and the face.

01:03:47.920 --> 01:03:49.870
- Wow.
- Or the neck.

01:03:49.870 --> 01:03:53.320
- Wow, so face, hands and bottoms of feet

01:03:53.320 --> 01:03:58.320
will cool you twice as
fast as putting cold packs

01:03:58.960 --> 01:04:02.000
into your armpits, your
groin, or back of neck?

01:04:02.000 --> 01:04:03.850
- So I like to give the analogy of

01:04:03.850 --> 01:04:06.220
if your car is overheating, okay?

01:04:06.220 --> 01:04:09.080
And you have a hose, a garden hose,

01:04:09.080 --> 01:04:12.110
where should you spray
your cooling system?

01:04:12.110 --> 01:04:14.960
Should you spray the
radiator or should you spray

01:04:14.960 --> 01:04:17.720
the tubes going in and
out of the radiator?

01:04:17.720 --> 01:04:20.230
Well, the rationale with
putting these cold packs

01:04:20.230 --> 01:04:22.160
in the axilla, the groin, and the neck,

01:04:22.160 --> 01:04:25.460
is that you're getting close
to the major arteries, okay?

01:04:25.460 --> 01:04:27.410
Sure. That's going to be effective.

01:04:27.410 --> 01:04:30.650
But it's much more effective
if you actually increase

01:04:30.650 --> 01:04:32.050
the heat loss capacity

01:04:32.050 --> 01:04:34.450
of the radiating surface, the radiators.

01:04:34.450 --> 01:04:38.710
- So you cool the hot stuff
heading toward the core?

01:04:38.710 --> 01:04:40.500
- That's essentially what

01:04:40.500 --> 01:04:43.253
the standard operating procedure is.

01:04:44.320 --> 01:04:46.610
That you hit the arteries.

01:04:46.610 --> 01:04:48.060
- Amazing.
- And the veins.

01:04:48.060 --> 01:04:48.950
Arteries and veins.

01:04:48.950 --> 01:04:52.510
- I'm going to just tell a
brief story that illustrates

01:04:52.510 --> 01:04:56.150
how almost everybody
gets this stuff wrong.

01:04:56.150 --> 01:04:57.610
And I'm going to use
that as an opportunity

01:04:57.610 --> 01:05:00.300
to ask you about heating,
deliberate heating,

01:05:00.300 --> 01:05:02.120
as opposed to deliberate cooling.

01:05:02.120 --> 01:05:04.460
So about four months ago,

01:05:04.460 --> 01:05:06.540
a friend of mine, incidentally,

01:05:06.540 --> 01:05:08.930
a guy who did nine
years in the SEAL Teams,

01:05:08.930 --> 01:05:10.870
really skilled cold water swimmer.

01:05:10.870 --> 01:05:12.770
We went out for a swim in the morning.

01:05:12.770 --> 01:05:16.580
I'm not nearly even close to the being

01:05:16.580 --> 01:05:19.780
in the same universe of
his output potential.

01:05:19.780 --> 01:05:21.870
We do these swims. I'm familiar with them.

01:05:21.870 --> 01:05:24.480
I got enough blubber on
me that I stay warm enough

01:05:24.480 --> 01:05:26.100
in the cold Pacific, no wetsuits.

01:05:26.100 --> 01:05:29.220
We do the morning cold swim
for about a mile or so.

01:05:29.220 --> 01:05:32.940
And we brought with us up a
young kid that I know real well

01:05:32.940 --> 01:05:35.440
that hangs out with us
sometimes and trains with us

01:05:35.440 --> 01:05:37.760
who's got very little body fat.

01:05:37.760 --> 01:05:40.030
He's just exceptionally lean,

01:05:40.030 --> 01:05:42.530
despite eating everything in sight, right?

01:05:42.530 --> 01:05:47.530
Teenager, great athlete,
great kid, great swimmer.

01:05:47.720 --> 01:05:49.140
So we're out there swimming

01:05:49.140 --> 01:05:51.500
and at some point we're talking to him

01:05:51.500 --> 01:05:54.050
and it's clear that he's gone hypothermic.

01:05:54.050 --> 01:05:55.320
He's slurring his words.

01:05:55.320 --> 01:05:58.570
He's not doing well. So
we get him onto the beach.

01:05:58.570 --> 01:06:00.823
His teeth are turning
yellow. He's quaking.

01:06:03.542 --> 01:06:06.250
His saliva is taken on that
consistency that's clear,

01:06:06.250 --> 01:06:07.930
like he's hypothermic.

01:06:07.930 --> 01:06:10.170
We go to the lifeguard station.

01:06:10.170 --> 01:06:12.550
Lifeguard says, "Okay,
let's get his vitals.

01:06:12.550 --> 01:06:13.383
Let's do all this."

01:06:13.383 --> 01:06:16.453
Meanwhile, trying stand next to him,

01:06:17.370 --> 01:06:19.700
and heat him up by heating up his torso.

01:06:19.700 --> 01:06:24.020
So there we are, pressing
against this guy, our friend,

01:06:24.020 --> 01:06:24.990
trying to heat him up.

01:06:24.990 --> 01:06:26.413
They get a blanket on him.

01:06:27.520 --> 01:06:30.950
I'm realizing he was barefoot.
His face was exposed.

01:06:30.950 --> 01:06:32.780
Although we did cover his
head with the blanket.

01:06:32.780 --> 01:06:33.750
And he eventually came back.

01:06:33.750 --> 01:06:36.740
We got some warm liquids
into him and he was okay.

01:06:36.740 --> 01:06:37.730
He was fine.

01:06:37.730 --> 01:06:38.700
I don't know whether his mother's

01:06:38.700 --> 01:06:41.240
ever going to let him swim with us again.

01:06:41.240 --> 01:06:43.800
If I ever disappear and go missing,

01:06:43.800 --> 01:06:46.550
it's because of that incident.

01:06:46.550 --> 01:06:48.820
Anyway, he did great.

01:06:48.820 --> 01:06:51.780
He recovered. He's back in
the water and doing well.

01:06:51.780 --> 01:06:55.970
But I realized that pretty
much everything from the point

01:06:55.970 --> 01:06:59.470
where we got back on the
beach until he was back

01:06:59.470 --> 01:07:01.410
to normal, we did incorrectly.

01:07:01.410 --> 01:07:03.240
We heated his torso.

01:07:03.240 --> 01:07:06.750
We left his extremities exposed.

01:07:06.750 --> 01:07:09.230
And we assumed we were
doing the right thing.

01:07:09.230 --> 01:07:11.100
And the lifeguard is a skilled lifeguard

01:07:11.100 --> 01:07:13.310
at a major public beach.

01:07:13.310 --> 01:07:15.500
So I guess the simple question is,

01:07:15.500 --> 01:07:16.980
did we get everything wrong?

01:07:16.980 --> 01:07:18.870
Did we get anything right?

01:07:18.870 --> 01:07:21.090
And what would have been the better option

01:07:21.090 --> 01:07:24.960
to heat up a hypothermic person in that,

01:07:24.960 --> 01:07:26.850
or similar situation?

01:07:26.850 --> 01:07:28.440
- Well, it's interesting you asked that,

01:07:28.440 --> 01:07:31.040
because that is the way we got

01:07:31.040 --> 01:07:34.393
into this area of investigation.

01:07:35.550 --> 01:07:37.860
I worked on how the hypothalamus

01:07:37.860 --> 01:07:40.970
regulates body temperature,
neurophysiology.

01:07:40.970 --> 01:07:45.680
And one day we were having a
discussion with a colleague

01:07:45.680 --> 01:07:48.070
in the department of anesthesia.

01:07:48.070 --> 01:07:51.990
And he jokingly said to my
colleague, he said, "Yeah,

01:07:51.990 --> 01:07:54.610
you guys think you know
so much about temperature.

01:07:54.610 --> 01:07:56.740
I bet you couldn't solve a problem we have

01:07:56.740 --> 01:07:58.430
in the recovery room."

01:07:58.430 --> 01:07:59.890
What's that?

01:07:59.890 --> 01:08:01.700
Well, the patient's come out of surgery.

01:08:01.700 --> 01:08:03.910
They're hypothermic and it takes us hours

01:08:03.910 --> 01:08:06.380
to get them to stop shivering.

01:08:06.380 --> 01:08:08.070
What do they do in the recovery room?

01:08:08.070 --> 01:08:09.820
Exactly what you suggested.

01:08:09.820 --> 01:08:13.123
They put on warm blankets,
they put on heat lamps,

01:08:14.330 --> 01:08:18.030
and it takes them an hour or
two hours to get these patients

01:08:18.030 --> 01:08:20.630
to stop shivering, to bring them back up.

01:08:20.630 --> 01:08:22.770
So we said, "Ah, it's a trivial problem."

01:08:22.770 --> 01:08:24.980
No. It's a hard problem.

01:08:24.980 --> 01:08:25.930
It's a hard problem,

01:08:25.930 --> 01:08:29.870
because when you're under
anesthesia, you're vasodilated.

01:08:29.870 --> 01:08:31.590
When you come out of anesthesia,

01:08:31.590 --> 01:08:33.640
you're hypothermic and you vasoconstrict,

01:08:34.613 --> 01:08:38.280
and that makes it very difficult
to get heat into the body.

01:08:38.280 --> 01:08:40.440
So we got the idea that, well,

01:08:40.440 --> 01:08:43.840
if we could just take one
appendage, like an arm,

01:08:43.840 --> 01:08:46.930
and we put it in a environment wrapped

01:08:46.930 --> 01:08:50.380
in a heating pad and a negative pressure,

01:08:50.380 --> 01:08:53.690
suction, that would pull
more blood into that limb,

01:08:53.690 --> 01:08:55.060
that blood would get heated

01:08:55.060 --> 01:08:57.400
and it would warm the body up faster.

01:08:57.400 --> 01:09:02.060
So my colleague built a prototype device.

01:09:02.060 --> 01:09:05.440
You couldn't get such a device
into the hospital these days.

01:09:05.440 --> 01:09:06.273
[Craig laughs]

01:09:06.273 --> 01:09:09.670
But we were with our
anesthesiologist friend,

01:09:09.670 --> 01:09:11.760
we took it into the recovery room.

01:09:11.760 --> 01:09:15.780
And the first thing that
patient said, "No way,

01:09:15.780 --> 01:09:17.660
you're not going to put
that on my patient."

01:09:17.660 --> 01:09:22.660
But he prevailed and first
patient didn't shiver at all,

01:09:23.040 --> 01:09:25.350
First patient was back
to normal temperature,

01:09:25.350 --> 01:09:28.160
core temperature in, I
think, it was eight minutes.

01:09:28.160 --> 01:09:29.310
- Amazing.
- Eight or nine minutes.

01:09:29.310 --> 01:09:30.860
- Is this now standard practice

01:09:30.860 --> 01:09:32.530
in hospitals?
- No. No, no.

01:09:32.530 --> 01:09:34.100
- So this is another example where,

01:09:34.100 --> 01:09:36.270
I don't get upset about the,

01:09:36.270 --> 01:09:38.990
although it's upsetting
to know that it's not,

01:09:38.990 --> 01:09:42.030
but I think that it's
yet another case where

01:09:43.026 --> 01:09:44.820
a fundamental problem exists.

01:09:44.820 --> 01:09:49.820
There's a science-based
solution that makes sense

01:09:50.880 --> 01:09:54.150
at the level of physiology,
engineering and practice,

01:09:54.150 --> 01:09:55.940
and yet it's not being done.

01:09:55.940 --> 01:09:56.850
- [Craig] Right.

01:09:56.850 --> 01:09:58.070
- And, I mean,

01:09:58.070 --> 01:09:59.590
that's a whole other discussion as to

01:09:59.590 --> 01:10:00.730
what the limitations are.

01:10:00.730 --> 01:10:01.827
Well, perhaps in,

01:10:01.827 --> 01:10:03.460
and I know a number of our listeners are

01:10:03.460 --> 01:10:05.250
in the healthcare and medical profession,

01:10:05.250 --> 01:10:06.410
as well as military, athletes,

01:10:06.410 --> 01:10:08.850
and just also standard
other types of jobs,

01:10:08.850 --> 01:10:11.470
civilians doing other types of work.

01:10:11.470 --> 01:10:14.050
It would be wonderful if
people understood this.

01:10:14.050 --> 01:10:15.613
So once again,

01:10:17.186 --> 01:10:20.040
is there a homegrown technology
that people could use?

01:10:20.040 --> 01:10:22.040
If somebody is hypothermic,

01:10:22.040 --> 01:10:24.960
what is going to be the best
way for them to warm up?

01:10:24.960 --> 01:10:28.030
Is it going to be holding
a nice warm mug of cocoa

01:10:28.030 --> 01:10:28.890
or something like that?

01:10:28.890 --> 01:10:31.940
But not too hot, I
guess, is again the idea.

01:10:31.940 --> 01:10:35.000
- Yeah, well, actually you can go hotter

01:10:36.420 --> 01:10:37.900
on the glabrous skin.

01:10:37.900 --> 01:10:38.900
- Oh, because it'll dilate?

01:10:38.900 --> 01:10:42.560
- Because it takes the
heat away faster, okay?

01:10:42.560 --> 01:10:44.330
But back to the anesthesia,

01:10:44.330 --> 01:10:47.760
what you can do is you can use warm pads.

01:10:47.760 --> 01:10:49.840
They have them in all hospitals,

01:10:49.840 --> 01:10:52.850
they have circulating
water, perfused pads.

01:10:52.850 --> 01:10:54.996
- Hot water bottle type stuff.
- Put them on the feet.

01:10:54.996 --> 01:10:55.829
Put them on the feet.
- So typically they'll

01:10:55.829 --> 01:10:57.970
slide them under your lower
back or something like that?

01:10:57.970 --> 01:11:00.220
- Yeah, put them on the feet.

01:11:00.220 --> 01:11:02.660
Okay, sure. That will do it.

01:11:02.660 --> 01:11:07.410
But it turns out that we
discovered through this work

01:11:07.410 --> 01:11:09.640
that it had nothing to
do with the whole arm.

01:11:09.640 --> 01:11:11.440
It was only the hand.

01:11:11.440 --> 01:11:13.580
And that's when we came to the realization

01:11:13.580 --> 01:11:15.440
of these special blood vessels.

01:11:15.440 --> 01:11:17.190
We didn't discover the blood vessels

01:11:17.190 --> 01:11:19.230
that are described in "Grey's Anatomy,"

01:11:19.230 --> 01:11:21.377
but nobody knew what they were for.

01:11:21.377 --> 01:11:23.180
- And you mentioned bears earlier

01:11:23.180 --> 01:11:24.903
and other hairy animals.

01:11:26.630 --> 01:11:27.463
Do they have

01:11:27.463 --> 01:11:29.595
these AVAs as well?
- Oh, yeah.

01:11:29.595 --> 01:11:31.020
- And I suppose we haven't defined AVAs.

01:11:31.020 --> 01:11:33.740
We've been pretty good about
the no acronyms rule. AVAs is?

