01:28:03.890 --> 01:28:05.920
But anyway, you asked about hibernation.

01:28:05.920 --> 01:28:10.080
So bears only go down to about 33,

01:28:10.080 --> 01:28:12.693
34 degrees centigrade in core temperature.

01:28:13.590 --> 01:28:15.450
And that's been argued that, well,

01:28:15.450 --> 01:28:18.290
they can't go lower because
they have so much insulation.

01:28:18.290 --> 01:28:21.110
They're so big, their surface
volume ratio, and so forth,

01:28:21.110 --> 01:28:22.640
and that's not true.

01:28:22.640 --> 01:28:27.380
They shiver, so if we have
a day like a minus 40,

01:28:27.380 --> 01:28:30.540
which you get up in Alaska,

01:28:30.540 --> 01:28:32.810
they will go through periods of shivering.

01:28:32.810 --> 01:28:35.990
And maintain a core temperature on 33-34.

01:28:35.990 --> 01:28:38.700
Now the ground squirrels and the marmots,

01:28:38.700 --> 01:28:41.193
which are smaller animals,

01:28:42.070 --> 01:28:44.380
they will drop down to a body temperature

01:28:45.340 --> 01:28:47.670
maybe within a degree of the environment.

01:28:47.670 --> 01:28:50.650
So they can go down to one
or two degrees centigrade

01:28:50.650 --> 01:28:54.360
just above freezing during
bouts of hibernation.

01:28:54.360 --> 01:28:56.760
So they'll stay in hibernation
for seven or eight days

01:28:56.760 --> 01:28:58.720
and they'll come back up
to normal body temperature

01:28:58.720 --> 01:29:00.070
for a day, then they'll go back down,

01:29:00.070 --> 01:29:01.060
and do another about-
