01:29:01.060 --> 01:29:02.740
that day when they're warming up again?

01:29:02.740 --> 01:29:03.739
Do go around-

01:29:03.739 --> 01:29:07.260
- They rearrange their nests,
eat, if they've stored food.

01:29:07.260 --> 01:29:09.160
Some species store lots of food.

01:29:09.160 --> 01:29:10.930
Others just depend on their fat.

01:29:10.930 --> 01:29:14.810
- A former mentor of mine,
my master's degree mentor,

01:29:14.810 --> 01:29:18.600
and a colleague and friend
of yours, Irving Zucker

01:29:18.600 --> 01:29:21.370
at UC Berkeley told me a story once,

01:29:21.370 --> 01:29:23.270
told me a lot of stories,
he tells great stories,

01:29:23.270 --> 01:29:24.103
as you know.

01:29:24.103 --> 01:29:26.180
He told me that when an animal comes out

01:29:26.180 --> 01:29:28.750
of hibernation periodically,

01:29:28.750 --> 01:29:31.490
that it's a very dramatic
thing to observe.

01:29:31.490 --> 01:29:33.240
That it's not like they wake up

01:29:33.240 --> 01:29:34.370
and yawn and look around,

01:29:34.370 --> 01:29:37.700
but it's like a complete
epileptic seizure.

01:29:37.700 --> 01:29:39.430
- Right.
- What what's going on?

01:29:39.430 --> 01:29:40.263
- Shiver.

01:29:40.263 --> 01:29:42.050
- It's just a very traumatic shiver.

01:29:42.050 --> 01:29:44.240
- So at the low temperatures,

01:29:44.240 --> 01:29:47.620
they cannot shiver because
the effect of temperature

01:29:47.620 --> 01:29:50.930
on the conduction of the
nerves and the muscle fiber.

01:29:50.930 --> 01:29:52.150
- So they're shut down basically?

01:29:52.150 --> 01:29:52.983
- They're shut down.

01:29:52.983 --> 01:29:54.350
So there they use brown fat.

01:29:54.350 --> 01:29:55.720
So they activate brown fat

01:29:55.720 --> 01:29:58.070
and then when they get up to
a temperature of maybe 15,

01:29:58.070 --> 01:29:59.870
16 degrees centigrade,

01:29:59.870 --> 01:30:02.670
then the shivering starts and
it gets very, very violent,

01:30:02.670 --> 01:30:05.363
but they're still asleep.

01:30:06.630 --> 01:30:08.143
- Do we shiver in our sleep?

01:30:09.140 --> 01:30:12.400
- I would imagine we do,
but it probably wakes us up.

01:30:12.400 --> 01:30:16.190
- Interesting, So the brown
fat is kind of like kindling?

01:30:16.190 --> 01:30:19.610
- The brown fat is a tissue

01:30:19.610 --> 01:30:24.040
which has lots of stored
energy, 'cause it's fat,

01:30:24.040 --> 01:30:26.960
but unlike our white fat, our regular fat,

01:30:26.960 --> 01:30:29.810
it also has lots of
these little powerhouses,

01:30:29.810 --> 01:30:32.790
mitochondria, and lots of blood supply.

01:30:32.790 --> 01:30:36.930
So essentially it is a
tissue just to produce heat.

01:30:36.930 --> 01:30:38.300
That's what it's there for.

01:30:38.300 --> 01:30:40.300
Now in these hibernators,

01:30:40.300 --> 01:30:43.610
there are big patches of
brown fat at certain locations

01:30:43.610 --> 01:30:46.840
that are critical, like
around the heart, for example.

01:30:46.840 --> 01:30:49.810
For us, the brown fat
is sort of distributed.

01:30:49.810 --> 01:30:51.790
So for many, many years,

